Mark H says:
> Cool. Up to know I've only been testing with the rdemo stuff (it is 
> fine for timing tests). My aim on this is going to be to get more or 
> less the speed of the RSAREF included in RIPEM 1.1-1.2 (or do 
> somewhat better) and at the same time have a much less ugly 
> implementation. At this point I have a lot of ugly experimental code 
> from tinkering with things, but really none of it is all that much 
> faster, especially in some sort of platform independent way (I don't 
> suppose that code that is significantly faster than the RSAREF in 
> RIPEM 1.2 on the HP9000/730 and is significantly slower on most other 
> things is worth much). 
> 
> With luck, I'll send it to you tomorrow. I'd like to get a 
> preliminary version out the door before or on Friday as I'll be out 
> of town and out of touch with email Sat 7 May-Sunday 15 May. This
> will give other people time to play with it, and perhaps optimise
> it for whatever platforms they have that I don't. 

Sounds good. Don't forget you can join the ripem-dev mailing list:


You can join the RIPEM developers' mailing list by sending
the message:

  subscribe ripem-dev <Your Name>

(e.g.  subscribe ripem-dev John Smith)

to the address:   listproc@ripem.msu.edu

Subsequently, you can send messages to the list by sending them to:

  ripem-dev@ripem.msu.edu

